In this example, national, ethnic/cultural, and religious identities seem to be intertwined. But is this necessarily the case? Skandrani et al. (2011) state that they did not find any differences between their participants that could be traced back to their countries of origin. Unfortunately, they do not state how they arrived at this conclusion. But let us take their conclusion for a fact: National identities based on the countries’ boundaries (“I am a Tunisian, Algerian, or Moroccan”) did not seem to matter in this case; more important were, according to Skandrani et al., regional identities (“I am Maghrebine”). What does “being a Maghrebine” include besides having parents that were born in Maghreb? In quite a few studies (e.g., Roudometof, 2002, or Schultz & Sackmann, 2001), individuals refer, when asked what their regional or national identities mean to them, to cultural characteristics. Cultural and national/regional identities can therefore stand for the same concepts. Schnell (1990), for example, examined 80 indicators for cultural or ethnic identities in migrant groups. These 80 indicators could be subsumed in the following categories:


language use and language mastery;

religious denomination and religious practice;

subjective affiliation to a certain ethnic group;

perception of discrimination;

contacts with the dominant and foreign ethnic groups;

contacts with the country of origin;

self-identification;

desire for ethnic cohesion;

desire for segregated living;

feeling of homelessness;

sympathy for different nations;

goals of education;

gender role orientation;

cultural habits (music, video, newspapers, food);

recognition of national holidays.
